<SAGPLayout title="2024 Distinguished Lectureship | SAGP">

<PageHero
  kicker="2024 Distinguished Lectureship"
  title="Professor Sir Geoffrey Lloyd"
  subtitle="“What is the Use of Ancient Philosophy?”"
  image="/assets/images/parthenon_night.jpg"
/>

<section class="section two-col">
  <div><h2>The 2024 lecture</h2></div>
  <div>
    <p><strong>Professor Sir Geoffrey Lloyd</strong>, Emeritus Professor of Ancient Philosophy and Science, University of Cambridge.</p>
    <p><strong>Date:</strong> January 15, 2025 · 12:00pm EST.</p>
    <p><strong>Commentator:</strong> Brad Inwood.</p>
    <p>This event was held via Zoom.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section two-col">
  <div><h2>Abstract</h2></div>
  <div>
    <p>
      Despite the obvious differences between social anthropology and the study of antiquity,
      Lloyd argues that anthropology provides an important model for getting the most out of
      ancient philosophy and science.
    </p>
    <p>
      The lecture considers how comparative approaches challenge assumptions about nature,
      univocity, proof, and mind/body dualism.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section two-col">
  <div><h2>Participants</h2></div>
  <div>
    <p>
      Geoffrey Lloyd is Emeritus Professor of Ancient Philosophy and Science at the University of Cambridge.
      His work spans Greek and Chinese philosophy, science, medicine, anthropology, and comparative studies.
    </p>
    <p>
      Brad Inwood is William Lampson Professor of Philosophy and Classics at Yale.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

</SAGPLayout>
